## Query Optimization Patterns

### Select Only Needed Columns

```ruby
# Bad: Load everything
articles = Article.all
articles.each { |a| puts a.title }

# Good: Load only needed columns
articles = Article.select(:id, :title)
articles.each { |a| puts a.title }
```

### Use pluck Instead of map

```ruby
# Bad: Loads all records
Article.all.map(&:title)

# Good: Single query, returns array
Article.pluck(:title)
```

### Use exists? Instead of any?

```ruby
# Bad: Loads records
Article.where(user_id: 1).any?

# Good: Doesn't load records
Article.where(user_id: 1).exists?
```

### Use find_each for Large Datasets

```ruby
# Bad: Loads all records into memory
Article.all.each { |a| process(a) }

# Good: Batch processing
Article.find_each { |a| process(a) }
```

### Avoid N+1 Queries

```ruby
# Bad: N+1 queries
articles = Article.all
articles.each { |a| puts a.user.name }

# Good: Eager load
articles = Article.includes(:user)
articles.each { |a| puts a.user.name }
```

### Use Counter Cache

```ruby
# Bad: Count query every time
user.articles.count

# Good: Use counter cache
class Article < ApplicationRecord
  belongs_to :user, counter_cache: true
end

user.articles_count  # No query!
```

